Hypothesis 3: Happiness and Age

happiness_vs_age <- responses %>%na.omit()%>% select(Age,Happiness.in.life)%>%group_by(Age)%>%summarise(avg_happiness=mean(Happiness.in.life))
plot(avg_happiness~Age,data=happiness_vs_age)

Hypothesis 4: Happiness and Fun with friends

happiness_fun.with.friends <- responses%>%select(Fun.with.friends, Happiness.in.life)%>%na.omit()
head(happiness_fun.with.friends)
##   Fun.with.friends Happiness.in.life
## 1                5                 4
## 2                4                 4
## 3                5                 4
## 4                2                 2
## 5                4                 3
## 6                3                 3
plot(jitter(Fun.with.friends)~jitter(Happiness.in.life),data=happiness_fun.with.friends)

The people who display moderate to high levels of happiness also tend to have more fun with friends, while those with lower levels of happiness are more likely to have less fun with friends.

Hypothesis 5: Fun with Friends and Internet

Fun.with.friends_vs_internet<- responses%>%select(Fun.with.friends,Internet)%>%na.omit()
plot(jitter(Fun.with.friends)~jitter(Internet),data=Fun.with.friends_vs_internet)

There seems to be a positive correlation between internet use and fun with friends.

Hypothesis 6: Pop Music and Comedy

Pop_vs_comedy <- responses%>%select(Pop,Comedy)%>%na.omit()
responses%>%na.omit()%>%group_by(Pop)%>%summarize(avg_comedy=mean(Comedy))
## # A tibble: 5  2
##     Pop avg_comedy
##   <int>      <dbl>
## 1     1   4.166667
## 2     2   4.390909
## 3     3   4.370968
## 4     4   4.570000
## 5     5   4.790541
plot(jitter(Pop)~jitter(Comedy),data=Pop_vs_comedy)

There seems to be a positive correlation between liking comedy and liking pop music, as evidenced both by the data grouped by average liking of commedy and by the jitter plot.
